<hl>
<seg id=1> China to Continue Policy of Opening Up Financial Markets </seg>
</hl>
<p>
<seg id=2> Xinhua Press Agency, Beijing, January 16, Telegram (Reporters Xu Xingtang and Qian Yuhong):  The head of the People's Bank of China, Dai Xianglong, said that China will continue its policy of opening up its financial markets. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=3> Dai Xianglong emphasized at the Chinese and foreign reporter news conference he held today that China will not abandon its policy of opening up its financial markets due to the financial upheaval of some countries in Southeast Asia. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=4> He said that a number of foreign banks and insurance companies had again established branch offices in China last year, and that by the end of the year, there were already more than 170 business financial agencies established in China with foreign capital. </seg>
<seg id=5> Branch offices of foreign banks and insurance companies in China will be suitably increased in the future, while preparations are being made for experiments in allowing foreign banks to handle business in Renminbi. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=6> At the same time, he also emphasized that more careful management would be conducted of the conditions imposed on applications for setting up business in China by foreign financial agencies, the qualifications of senior personnel, and the legality of their operations. </seg>
</p>
<p>
<seg id=7> He said that since there has never been a time schedule for convertibility under Renminbi capital projects, there is no issue of extending the process due to the Southeast Asian financial crisis. </seg>
<seg id=8> But with regard to the development of capital projects, the lessons of the Southeast Asian financial crisis and a more careful attitude will be adopted. </seg>
</p>
